        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Finding 'market inefficiencies'</h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Before Figma became the industry-standard design tool, its origins were far from what they are today. <strong>Initially, Dylan Field and Evan Wallace were exploring ideas in computer graphics, working on projects like drones and a meme generator</strong>. Their approach to creating a product or service was based on finding what they called a <strong>‚Äòmarket inefficiency,‚Äô</strong> a gap in the market that could be filled with an innovative solution.
          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/figma-cofounders-dylan-fields-evan-wallace-photo.png" alt="Co-founders of Figma, Dylan Fields (left) and Evan Wallace (right)" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>Co-founders of Figma, Dylan Fields (left) and Evan Wallace (right). Credits: Brown CS: Posts </i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Field and Wallace met at Brown University. Field secured a <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-29-03-2025-1-thiel-fellowship?source=website" target="_blank">Thiel Fellowship</a>, and he intended to start a drone company and hoped to solve key limitations, including software, battery life, and FAA regulations. However, when Wallace joined the project, he convinced Field that <strong>drones weren‚Äôt as promising as he initially thought</strong>. As they <strong>shifted their focus to a meme generator</strong>, they questioned whether it was worth spending their entire two-year grant.  
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">This was the turning point where Figma started to take shape. They recognized a much bigger inefficiency in the market; <strong>designers were stuck using outdated tools that required constantly sending static files back and forth</strong>. Initially, they prioritized real-time collaboration to eliminate version confusion and endless email chains. They understood early on that designers needed faster feedback loops and a shared space for real-time communication to create the best possible products.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column> 
    </mj-section>


