          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Swimming against the tide</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">In the early days, Figma faced skepticism. One investor in a potential seed round passed on the opportunity, telling the team, <strong>‚ÄúI just don‚Äôt think you know what you‚Äôre doing yet.‚Äù</strong> In addition to building a product that was difficult to explain, <strong>they boldly rejected the Lean Startup methodology, which was widely followed in Silicon Valley and the startup world</strong>.
         </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"><a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-29-03-2025-2-lean-startup-methodology?source=website" target="_blank">Lean Startup methodology</a> emphasizes rapid experimentation, iterative product releases, and validated learning to determine if a business model is viable quickly. But Field and Wallace chose to swim against the tide. <strong>They believed that for their product to succeed, they had to present a fully developed version rather than an early iteration</strong>. They understood that, in their case, a minimum viable product might not be enough to convince users of its full potential.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">If they had strictly followed Lean Startup principles, their idea could have been dismissed in the early stages of market research because established competitors like Sketch and Adobe were already doing something similar. Despite this, they did not entirely ignore user feedback. <strong>They gathered insights from developers, designers, and early users to refine their product, internally implementing the "<a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-29-03-2025-3-build-measure-learn?source=website" target="_blank">Build, Measure, Learn</a>" philosophy</strong>. However, they waited until their product was close to completion before actively pitching it to investors.</p>
          </mj-text>
          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Breaking into the market</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Even after launching Figma, Field and Wallace faced a <strong>major challenge: getting users to adopt their product</strong>. They needed a strong user base to vouch for its utility, but convincing people to switch to something new was no easy task. Field and Wallace understood that their biggest hurdle was <strong>brand awareness</strong>.</p>
          </mj-text>

          <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/figma-suite-tools-replace-asset-creation-design-tools.png" alt="Visual depicting the suite of tools that Figma replaced ‚Äî it extended well beyond just asset creation" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
           <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>Visual depicting the suite of tools that Figma replaced ‚Äî it extended well beyond just asset creation. Credits: Craft Ventures</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>

          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">To solve this, they decided to lower the barrier to entry. <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-29-03-2025-4-field-said?source=website" target="_blank">Field said</a>, <strong>‚ÄúIf folks weren‚Äôt ready to use Figma full-time in their day job, they could use Figma for free for a side project.‚Äù</strong> Figma also engaged directly with potential users, holding customer discovery sessions, gathering feedback, and running product demos. Their first breakthrough came when they signed Coda as a customer, proving that their product had real-world demand.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Finally, after several years of development and testing, <strong>Figma officially launched in 2016</strong>. Thanks to its innovative features and user-friendly interface, it quickly gained traction among designers and teams. Field and Wallace proved that sometimes breaking the rules can lead to groundbreaking success. <strong>As of April 2024, notable business customers of Figma included Microsoft, Stripe, Netflix, Spotify, Patagonia, and Puma, among others</strong>.</p>
          </mj-text> 
      </mj-column>
